XII. 1 There remains to be considered, equality in the thing itself, consisting in this, that though nothing was concealed which ought to have been told, nor more exacted than was thought to be due3 yet if there be an inequality in the thing itself, though without any fault of the parties3 if for instance there was some latent defect, or some error about the price, that also is to be made good, and the difference paid to him who suffers by it; because, in a contremet, there was intended, or ought to have been, that each party should have the same value.

2 The Roman law appointed this as the rule, not in every ine- quality, (for the law does not follow matters to their smallest dimen- sions, and also wishes to obviate the multitude of lawsuits,) but in a grave inequality, as for instance, one which exceeds the half of the fair price.
